tions</span></span></a><button class="navbar-toggler" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#navbarNavAltMarkup" aria-controls="navbarNavAltMarkup" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle navigation"><span class="navbar-toggler-icon"/></button><div class="collapse navbar-collapse justify-content-end" id="navbarNavAltMarkup"><div class="navbar-nav"><a class="nav-link" href="/">Home</a><a class="nav-link" href="/browse.html">Browse</a><a class="nav-link" href="/documentation.html">Documentation</a><a class="nav-link" href="/about.html">About</a><a class="nav-link" href="/contact.html">Contact Us</a></div></div></div></nav><div class="container my-5"><div class="interior-content"><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns" class="padding-top"><h1>SPEAR Factoids about <span id="title"><span><span class="tei-prefLabel" xml:lang="en" lang="en" dir="ltr">Pilgrimage</span></span></span></h1></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns"><div style="margin:0 1em 1em; color: #999999;"><small><p><span class="srp-label"><strong>Syriaca.org URI</strong></span>: <span id="syriaca-id"><a href="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/pilgrimage">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/pilgrimage</a></span></p></small></div></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns" class="row"><div class="col-md-8"><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span>Susan put
                            her soul into the Lord's hands and fled from  her parents.
                         <a href="/819-13" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span> After three or four miles, Susan came upon a
                            large party of  women and
                                men travelling to Jerusalem and joined
                            them.  <a href="/819-14" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span> After worshipping in Jerusalem,  the men and women in Susan's
                                party tried unsuccessfully to bring  Susan back with
                            them.  <a href="/819-16" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span>Leontius
                            grew up with John of
                                Ephesus from childhood.  <a href="/830-17" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span> Many began to flock to Mare for a blessing, and they were amazed at his prayer
                            and dress. Mare refused to eat anything that was not produced by the
                            labour of his hands.  <a href="/828-20" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span>Anonymi 3664
                            came to Susan
                            and Anonymi
                                3352 from Alexandria and from Libya.  <a href="/819-55" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span>Addai and
                                Abraham
                            went on pilgrimage for several years. <a href="/814-6" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span>Leontius left his
                            monastery in the same manner as his fellow monastic Qashish to travel
                            alone to the eastern, southern, and western regions in the capacity of a
                            wandering monk (aksnāyutā) for many years, while both let their hair
                            grow long in a worldly fashion, lest they be honored as monks.  <a href="/830-7" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span> After many years of wandering, Leontius and
                                Qashish
                            joined the company of John
                                of Ephesus at the Monastery of Yoḥannan
                                Urṭaya and lived there for about twenty years until his
                            death.  <a href="/830-8" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span> At the age of eight, Susan wanted to go on pilgrimage, but Susan's parents 
                            denied her permission.  <a href="/819-9" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">event: </span>Leontius was
                            buried alongside of the
                                Blessed Aaron at the Monastery of Yoḥannan
                                Urṭaya <a href="/830-9" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><div class="citation"><h3>How to cite:</h3><span class="element">
